					<h4>Prairie Dog Beat</h4>
		
		<h1>Boulder isn&#8217;t the only place with Prairie Dog Woes</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 12-11-06</p>
			
							<table width="25" align="right" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
					<tr>
						<td>&nbsp;</td>
						<td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/thumbnails_feature/prairie_dog2_thumb.jpg" style="float: right; margin: 3px;" border="0" alt="" width="227" height="150" /></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>

											<tr>
							<td>&nbsp;</td>
							<td class="image-caption" align="right">Caption: Black-tailed prairie dog, photo courtesy of the Colorado Division of Wildlife.</td>
						</tr>
					
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>
				</table>
			
							Boulder often feels like the epicenter of prairie dog controversy.  When the persistent little doggers <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/index.php/city/article/6858/C94/L94" title="burrow under Little League fields">burrow under Little League fields</a> and <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/index.php/topic/article/2681/C147/L38" title="come down with plague">come down with plague</a>, residents disagree over whether they should be killed or allowed to go about their business.  In Sunday's <i>New York Times</i>, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/11/us/11prairiedogs.html?pagewanted=1&_r=1" title="Felicity Barringer reported">Felicity Barringer reported</a> about a prairie dog hullabaloo in Russell Springs, Kansas, proving that the little mammals are inciting neighbors to argue throughout the Great Plains as well as the Rocky Mountain states.  <br />
<br />
Barringer writes that ranchers Larry Haverfield and Gordon Barnhardt, whose land is covered with prairie dogs, "want the 5,500-acre colony on their property to flourish, for the good of the land and for the eventual delectation of black-footed ferrets. The ferrets, an endangered mammal, thrive on a diet of prairie dogs."  Their neighbors disagree with their decision, as prairie dogs demonstrate little respect for property lines.  And the beat goes on.
						<b>[End of article]</b>
